NHS England sought to appoint up to 5 providers to a new framework (Framework 3) to continue to deliver a behaviour change programme nationally, with the ability to offer face to face, digital (app web based) and remote (video/tele conferencing) service delivery.
This new framework will also aim to:
• Widen access and choice of prevention services, particularly for working age and younger cohorts, and individuals who experience health inequalities and inequity in access in communities;
• Continue improving retention on interventions to maximise benefit;
• Ensure continued universal availability of services for the benefit of eligible citizens;
• Encourage innovation to improve quality and effectiveness of services; and
• Achieve best value for money and sustainability of services.

QAA is looking to appoint a recruitment agency to assist with a search for a series of new non-executive positions:  the chair and members of the new Designated Quality Body for England Board (DQBE Board).  The agency will need to advertise the positions and undertake a search;  we would expect the agency to be able to draw on an existing database of appropriate contacts, including in the higher education sector.

We are seeking to appoint:
-	A chair, who will not be a member of the QAA Board, but may be invited to attend part or all of specific QAA Board meetings;
-	Three or four members from English Universities, drawn from different parts of the higher education sector and bringing a diverse range of experience; 
-	One member who has current or recent status as a student in England (normally with some experience of student representative work) and who does not serve on QAA's Board or other Committees;
-	One member from a College with HE degree-awarding powers in England;
-	One member from a validated or franchised provider of higher education in England;
-	If this expertise is not provided by another member, one member from a professional body (PSRB).
  
The Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education (QAA) is a charity, the independent quality body for UK higher education and one of the world's experts in quality assurance.  We work with governments, agencies and institutions globally to benefit UK higher education and its international reputation.  We work across all four nations of the UK, but in England we have two distinct roles, separated by an ethical barrier.  One of these is the Designated Quality Body function, through which we, as the body designated by the Secretary of State, assess quality and standards in English higher education to inform regulatory decision-making by the regulator, the Office for Students.  This is entirely separate from our work in partnership with our members to secure academic standards, enhance quality and promote the reputation of UK higher education across the world.  QAA announced the creation of the DQBE Board in March 2022, following an internal review of our strategic and operational models.  

This procurement will be managed electronically by QAA's Governance Team. The closing date for tenders is 10th May at 5pm.  

To participate in this procurement, please email governance@qaa.ac.uk.  If you have any enquiries about this tender, please email Tom Yates, Director of Corporate Affairs:  t.yates@qaa.ac.uk

Supply, manufacture, construct, implement, deliver, operate and decommission the TM required for Birmingham 2022 Commonwealth Games at competition and non-competition venues, together with any other CWG sites or locations requiring TM measures.

The services to be delivered as part of this are, but not exclusive to:

- Project Management;
- Traffic Management Services;
- Temporary traffic management equipment
- Ancillary Site Equipment;
- Manufacture and supply of statutory, wayfinding and information signage
- Specialist labour to operate equipment including Vehicle Permit Checkpoints (VPC) at all specified locations;
- Specialist labour to manage crowd movements at venues and transport hubs; and
- Non-specialist labour (traffic stewards) to manage access to venue car parks.

The West Midlands Combined Authority (WMCA) is seeking to appoint a Contractor to undertake the delivery of the Local Area Traffic Management and Parking (LATMP) plans and the Games Route Network (GRN) for the Birmingham 2022 Commonwealth Games (CWG). In addition, the appointed Contractor will provide on-going support as and when required to the TfWM Games Traffic Management (TM) team until the end of the CWG.

The Contract is for the provision of Prison Operator Services at HMP & YOI Parc.

The Contractor will be responsible for the provision of a safe, decent, secure operating model and regime that specifically meets the needs of various prisoner cohorts, whilst providing a platform for prisoner opportunities to tackle the causes of their offending and support their release back into communities.

The services will include:
- Ensuring the safety and wellbeing of prisoners on their arrival, early days and induction period and integrating them into the environment and regime;
- Delivery of a child-centred approach to enable effective care and management of Children, helping to achieve constructive resettlement, public protection and better outcomes for Children;
- Delivery of Industries, Interventions and Prison Work which will deliver outcomes related to effective rehabilitation and resettlement;
- Preparing prisoners for release and ensuring continuity of care and service delivery upon, and post-, release;
- Delivery of Property and Facilities Management services, including sustainability outcomes with due regard to the environment; and
- Investment in the infrastructure of the prison, to improve and future proof the asset and enable effective service provision in future.

Project aim: To assess how HLS and CS agreements contribute towards environmental outcomes across multiple scheme objectives.

The objectives of this project are to:
-	understand how delivery of environmental outcomes have changed over time; 
-	explore the environmental effectiveness of HLS and CS at option and agreement level over time; 
-	explore the extent to which the circumstance (e.g. farm type, ownership etc.), commitment and understanding of the agreement holder has influenced the outcome;
-	evaluate the patterns of outcome from across the agreement sample to provide an overall assessment of the environmental effectiveness of HLS and CS.
